        "body": "Creating latte art requires properly steamed milk with a smooth, velvety microfoam. Here's a breakdown of the key steps:\n\n1. **Start with Cold Milk:** Use fresh, cold milk (whole milk is easiest, but others work) for the best results.\n2. **Purge the Steam Wand:** Briefly open the steam wand to release any condensation.\n3. **Position the Wand:** Submerge the tip of the steam wand just below the surface of the milk. Start steaming.\n4. **Stretching the Milk:** As the milk heats, lower the pitcher to introduce air and create foam. You should hear a hissing sound. Aim to increase the volume of the milk by about 50%.\n5. **Texturing the Milk:** Once you have enough foam, submerge the steam wand deeper into the milk. Create a whirlpool to incorporate the foam and create a smooth, glossy texture. The milk should be hot but not scalded.\n6. **Clean the Wand:** Immediately wipe down the steam wand with a damp cloth and purge it again to prevent milk buildup.\n7. **Swirl and Tap:** Swirl the milk in the pitcher to ensure even texture. Tap the pitcher on the counter to release any large bubbles.\n8. **Pouring:** Practice makes perfect! Start with simple designs and gradually work your way up to more complex latte art."
